<h1>@HI{{te}} conjunctive forms</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vte{{}},
<li> @Aistem{{}}kute,
<li> @Anastem{{}}de,
<li> @N{{}}de,
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The conjunctive forms are used to connect sentences. The sentences are joined in the order 
that the actions mentioned in them occur. The tense of the whole sentence is determined by
the tense form of the end ofthe sentence.
</p>

<p>
These forms can be used to connect sentences with different topics. However, if the sentences
express contradictory notions, then this form cannot be used and <a href="grammar-ga-conjunction.html">@HI{{ga}}</a>
should be used instead.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{gods^door}}he @KJ{{going}}tte, @KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}wo @KJ{{see}}te,
      o@KJ{{tea}}wo @KJ{{drink}}mimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I went to Kobe, saw a film and drank tea.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kinouha @KJ{{heavens^spirit}}ga yokute, @KJ{{sultry}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yesterday it was fine and hot.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{nara^good}}ha @KJ{{quiet}}kade, kireina @KJ{{town}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Nara is a quiet and beautiful town.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

